    <h3 class="subtitle">Steps:</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>1. Cut or tear the used paper into small pieces. Typically, pieces that are 2-3 inches in size should suffice.</li><li>2. Submerge the paper pieces in a large bowl of water. Allow the paper to soak until it becomes very soft. This could take a few hours, but soaking overnight is best.</li><li>3. Remove the paper from the water, squeezing out the excess water gently.</li><li>4. Spread a thin layer of food-safe glue on one side of each paper piece.</li><li>5. Cover the surface of a large bowl or plate with plastic wrap or cling film, ensuring it's entirely covered.</li><li>6. Place another slightly smaller bowl or some weight on top of the paper layers to ensure they are compressed.</li><li>7. Allow the paper plate to dry in a well-ventilated area. This might take a day or even longer, depending on the climate and the thickness of the paper.</li><li>8. Once the paper plate is completely dry, remove it from the bowl or plate and trim the edges with scissors.</li><li>9. Add personal touches using acrylic paints or other decorative materials if desired.</li><li>10. To make the paper plate more durable, consider sealing it with a non-toxic clear sealant.</li>
    </ol>

